					<strong><a title="permalink: re: Versioning Databases – The Baseline" href="/Blogs/scott/archive/2008/02/01/versioning-databases-the-baseline.aspx#3088">#</a>&nbsp;<a name="3088"></a>re: Versioning Databases – The Baseline</strong>
					<div class="info">by <a id="comments_ascx_CommentList_ctl13_NameLink" title="Bob Archer" target="_blank">Bob Archer</a> at 2/4/2008 6:50 PM</div>
					<hr style="clear:left; visibility:hidden;" />
				</div>
					<div class="post">
						We use a tool called DbGhost. It is designed for managing DB change and source controlling the schema/data scripts.<br /><br />We only generate change scripts for each release version... not for each build. For the interium build versions each dev has a copy of Dbghost and can use it to update thier local db from script updated from subversion. Or, they can grab the &quot;template&quot; db's backup to get up to date if they'd like.<br /><br />This works very well for us. DbGhost also has a command line interface which makes it easy to run from NAnt or whatever build tool you use. 
					</div>
